<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS,</BOLD> The Durham Regional Police Services Board, Leon Lynch, John Johnson Allan, Cindi Bradley, Daniel Anthony Denyer, Jim Burrows, Jeff Kennedy, David Kimmerly, And Dianne Jennings, appeal to the Court of Appeal for Ontario from the order of the Divisional Court dated February 21, 2018 made at Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS ASK</BOLD> that the order be set aside and an order be granted as follows:</P>
<P>1. Restoring the order of Matheson J. dated November 29, 2016 which dismissed the motion by the Defendants, Attorney General, of Ontario, Michael Hill, and John Scott, for an order dismissing the Appellants' Crossclaim as against them;</P>
<P>2. Awarding costs of this appeal, the motion for leave to appeal to this court, the appeal to the Divisional Court, and the motion for leave to appeal to the Divisional Court, to the Appellants;</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The Plaintiff commenced an action for damages allegedly caused by an undercover &ldquo;Mr. Big&rdquo; investigation of which he was the subject, pertaining to an unsolved murder in 1974. The investigation allegedly included, among other things, a scenario referred to in the Statement of Claim as the &ldquo;body dump&rdquo; in which the Plaintiff was made to believe that he was participating in the disposal of a corpse, which would later form the basis for discussions about whether he was involved in the 1974 murder;</P>
<P>2. In addition to the police officers who conducted the investigation, the Plaintiff also sued the Attorney General of Ontario and two Crown Attorneys (collectively the &ldquo;Attorney General Defendants&rdquo;) based on allegedly negligent legal advice provided by the Crown Attorneys to the police during the investigation and prior to commencement of the resulting prosecution for murder. The Plaintiff did not claim for malicious prosecution, however, and did not sue the separate Crown Attorneys who later had carriage of the criminal prosecution;</P>
<P>3. The Appellants crossclaimed against the Attorney General Defendants, alleging among other things that:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;The Crown Attorney's Office was involved from the commencement of the UCO [undercover operation] until its conclusion. This included consultation by the DRPS [Durham Regional Police Service] with respect to the conduct of the UCO and the provision by the Crown of legal advice and guidance with respect to same, on which the DRPS relied in good faith. The Crown also handled preparation of the applications for judicial authorization of covert surveillance. The authorizations lasted for approximately 60 days, and each successive application outlined in detail the investigation that had been conducted up to that time&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;The Crown Attorney's Office, which had been providing approval of proposed scenarios since the inception of the UCO, also approved the &lsquo;body dump&rsquo; scenario following consultation by the DRPS&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;These Defendants state that throughout the investigative and charging process, the investigative methodology and potential charges involving the Plaintiff were reviewed with the Crown Attorney's Office in the context of a solicitor-client relationship. These Defendants state that in proceeding with the investigation and reaching their conclusions that they had reasonable and probable grounds for charging the Plaintiff, these Defendants relied in good faith upon the legal advice and guidance provided by the Crown. To the extent that the Crown provided either improper or inadequate advice, these Defendants could not foresee that any component of the investigation would result in any alleged breach of duty to the Plaintiff or any alleged breach of the Plaintiff's rights&rdquo;;</P1></P>
<P>4. The Attorney General Defendants brought a Rule 21 motion to strike both the Plaintiff's claim and the Appellants' Crossclaim as against them. On November 29, 2016, Matheson J. ordered the Plaintiff's claim struck out as against the Attorney General Defendants, but refused to strike out the Appellants' Crossclaim based on negligent legal advice. In particular, Matheson J. concluded that it was not &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; either that prosecutorial immunity applied to the Crossclaim or that the Crown Attorneys did not owe a duty of care to the police;</P>
<P>5. The Attorney General Defendants brought a motion for, and were granted, leave to appeal to the Divisional Court;</P>
<P>6. By order dated February 21, 2018, the Divisional Court reversed Matheson J.'s order and dismissed the Appellants' Crossclaim as against the Attorney General Defendants;</P>
<P>7. In so ordering, the Divisional Court held: &ldquo;No appellate case has suggested that Crown Attorneys may be liable for negligence based on the legal advice they have provided to the police in the course of an investigation leading to criminal charges&rdquo;. The court further held that &ldquo;policy considerations&rdquo; supported the conclusion that Crown Attorneys should be immune from such claims. Based on the foregoing, the court held that it was &ldquo;not necessary to discuss the second issue&rdquo;, namely, whether it was also plain and obvious that Crown Attorneys could never owe a duty of care to police officers to whom they provide legal advice regarding the conduct of an investigation of an identified suspect;</P>
<P>8. With respect, the Divisional Court made the following errors of law:
<P1>(a) It held that the Crown Attorneys' immunity from the Crossclaim was &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; in the absence of any reported case in Canada, prior to Matheson J.'s decision, which considered (let alone determined) whether a Crown Attorney can be held liable for negligent legal advice provided to the police regarding the conduct of an investigation;</P1>
<P1>(b) It failed to undertake any analysis of the relevant Supreme Court of Canada jurisprudence which has delineated the scope of prosecutorial immunity. As developed in the case law, the immunity is a function of the constitutional independence of Crown Attorneys when making decisions about whether and how to prosecute criminal charges. It is not &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; that this immunity would necessarily extend to legal advice regarding a police investigation. That type of involvement has never been suggested by the court to attract constitutional independence or immunity;</P1>
<P1>(c) Although it declined to consider whether any duty of care could exist in the circumstances, it held that broad-based &ldquo;policy considerations&rdquo;&mdash;including &ldquo;the concern that Crown Attorneys will be diverted from their important public duties&rdquo; and a &ldquo;chilling effect&rdquo;&mdash;buttressed the conclusion that Crown Attorneys should be immune from claims for negligent legal advice provided to police regarding the investigation of a suspect. This approach is contrary to the latest guidance from the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Deloitte &amp; Touche v. Livent Inc. (Receiver of)</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 63</CITE></CASEREF>, that it should only be in &ldquo;rare cases&rdquo; that such policy considerations preclude liability when an individual's negligence causes reasonably foreseeable injury to another individual with whom he or she shares a close and direct relationship. Based on the allegations in this case, there can be no doubt that the Crown Attorneys were in a close and direct relationship with the police officers to whom they provided legal advice, and that harm to the Plaintiff&mdash;for which the police are now being sued&mdash;was a reasonably foreseeable consequence of negligent legal advice regarding the investigative techniques to be used;</P1></P>
<P>9. This court has held that the very high threshold for the moving party on a Rule 21 motion will not be met in the absence of binding case law which &ldquo;establishes definitively&rdquo; that no actionable claim exists;</P>
<P>10. This is the first time that this factual matrix has come before an appellate court in this country. It raises significant questions of law, for which no clear precedent exists;</P>
<P>11. Whereas Matheson J. appropriately left the issue open to be argued and determined on an evidentiary record, the Divisional Court opted to do so on the pleadings alone. It made the final determination that prosecutorial immunity shields Crown Attorneys from any possible claim by the police for legal advice given to the police regarding the conduct of an investigation and on which the police rely in good faith in conducting that investigation. In doing so, the Divisional Court ruled out any future judicial consideration, on a proper evidentiary record, of the novel legal issues that arise in this context;</P>
<P>12. These are issues of significant public importance, with far reaching implications for the assessment of liability in cases where Crown Attorneys and police collaborate in major crime investigations. The Divisional Court erred in law in summarily disposing of these legally novel and complex issues on a pleadings motion under Rule 21;</P>
<P>13. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. Leave to appeal from the Court of Appeal for Ontario was granted on July 5, 2018 pursuant to s. 6(1)(a) of the Courts of Justice Act and Rule 61.03.1 of the Rules of Civil Procedure.</P>
