<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS,</BOLD> York Regional Police Service Board and YRP #1 (&ldquo;<BOLD>the YRP Defendants</BOLD>&rdquo;), appeal to the Court of Appeal for Ontario from the Order of the Divisional Court dated February 21, 2018 made at Toronto, Ontario,</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APELLANTS ASK</BOLD> that the Order be set aside and an Order be granted as follows:</P>
<P>I, Restoring the Order of Matheson J. (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Motion Judge</BOLD>&rdquo;) dated November 29, 2016, dismissing the Crown Defend ants' motion to strike the crossclaim of the Durham Regional Police Services' and corresponding officers' crossclaim (&ldquo;the <BOLD>DRPS Defendants</BOLD>&rdquo;), together with the anticipated crossclaim of the YRP Defendants;</P>
<P>2, Awarding costs of the appeal, the motion for leave to appeal to this court, the appeal to the Divisional Court, and the motion for leave to appeal to the Divisional Court to the Appellants.</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF THE APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>4. The plaintiff's action arises out of the investigation and charging of the plaintiff for the first degree murder of his neighbour, Beverly Smith, The investigation included a &ldquo;Mr. Big&rdquo; operation, which involved officers from the Durham Regional Police Services Board, as well as one YRP Officer, YRP #1, who was on secondment to the DRPS during the investigation. At the criminal the trial judge excluded the plaintiff's confession and the plaintiff was acquitted of the murder charge.</P>
<P>5. The plaintiff subsequently brought a claim for negligent investigation, among other things, against the police officers involved, the DRPS, the YRP, Her Majesty the Queen (on behalf of the Ontario Provincial Police) and the Attorney General Defendants. The plaintiff's claim against the Attorney General Defendants was struck by the Motion Judge and the plaintiff abandoned his appeal in this regard.</P>
<P>6. The DRPS also brought a crossclaim against the Attorney General Defendants, seeking contribution and indemnity against the Attorney General Defendants arising out of the legal advice provided by the Crown Attorneys (Hill and Scott) to the police concerning steps to be taken during the investigation of the plaintiff. While the YRP Defendants have not yet filed a crossclaim against the Attorney General Defendants (the limitation period has bees tolled in this regard pending the outcome of the within appeal), the YRP Defendants have at all times indicated an intention to commence a crossclaim, similar to that of the DRPS Defendants. The Motion Judge has allowed the YKP to bring their claim against the Attorney General Defendants using the crossclaim procedure, rather than by issuing a third party claim.</P>
<P>7. Having struck the plaintiff's claim against the Attorney General Defendants, the Motion Judge struck the DRPS Defendants' claim for contribution against the Attorney General Defendants. She did not, however, strike the claim for indemnity as it was not &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; that the police cannot seek indemnity from the Crown in respect of negligent legal advice received during the course of an investigation.</P>
<P>8. The Attorney General Defendants successfully sought leave to appeal to the Divisional Court arguing, among other things, that the appeal raised issues of general importance with far reaching implications for the potential liability of Crown Attorneys.</P>
<P>9. For reasons released February 21, 2018 (<CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Attorney General of Ontario</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 933</CITE></CASEREF>), the appeal was allowed by the Divisional Court which concluded that the Motion Judge had erred in allowing the crossclaim for indemnity of the DRPS Defendants to continue. The Divisional Court found that it was plain and obvious that the DRPS Defendants' crossclaim would fail due to the scope of prosecutorial immunity. Although the Motion Judge had done so, the Divisional Court declined to address whether the allegation that Crown Attorneys have a duty of care in tort to the police had a reasonable prospect of success.</P>
<P>10. With respect, the Divisional Court made the following errors:</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Teston a Rule 21 Motion to Strike</EM></TI>
<P><P1>(a) The Divisional Court erred in failing to apply the appropriate test for considering the tenability of a claim on a motion to Strike, The Divisional Court's decision is premised, in part, on the fact that there is no binding authority suggesting that Crown Attorneys may be liable in negligence based on the legal advice provided to police in the court of an investigation. The novelty of a claim is not determinative on a motion to strike. The approach taken on a motion to strike must be generous and err on the side of per mitting novel, but arguable claims to proceed to trial with the benefit of a full evidentiary record.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>In the Analysis of the&ldquo;Prosecutorial Immunity&rdquo;</EM></TI>
<P><P1>(b) The Divisional Court erred in finding that it is plain and obvious that prosecutorial immunity applies to the crossclaim of the DRPS Defendants.</P1>
<P1>(c) The Division Court erred in relying on a so called &ldquo;prohibition&rdquo; against the approach&rdquo; to assessing Crown Attorney liability as discussed in <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 S.C.R. 170</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Nelles</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), which addressed the issue of whether prosecuting Crown Attorneys enjoyed absolute immunity. In <EM>Nelles</EM>, the Court addressed the propriety of applying a &ldquo;functional approach&rdquo; in the limited context of addressing absolute Crown immunity. The Court rejected the &ldquo;fractional&rdquo; argument on the basis that any action performed maliciously whether or not part of the prosecutorial function should give rise to a claim for malicious prosecution. <EM>Nelles</EM> did not create an all-encompassing &ldquo;prohibition&rdquo; against distinguishing between the prosecutorial function of Crown Attorneys and their expanding investigative role advising police.</P1>
<P1>(d) The Divisional Court erred In failing; to address the impact of Hill v. <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton Wentworth (Regional Minicipality) Regional Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 41</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Hill</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;) on Crown Attorneys and their role in the investigation of a suspect. The Divisional Court decision is irreconcilable with the recognition of a duty of care by police offices to suspects being investigated and creates a void in terms of a suspect's ability to receive compensation in a situation where police rely on the legal advice of a Crown Attorney, therefore meeting the standard of care, and that advice turns out to have been negligent.</P1>
<P1>(e) The Divisional Court erred in finding that there are no countervailing policy concerns that public confidence in the administration of justice will be eroded if Crown Attorneys are not held liable because they have been negligent in providing legal advice. The administration of justice requires that legal advice provided by the Crown Attorneys be held to standard of reasonableness given the importance of the interests at stake. As the Motion Judge aptly stated in her reasons, &ldquo;[t]he provision of competent independent legal advice to the police would, it seems to me, serve the administration of justice. How would legal responsibility for negligent advice interfere?&rdquo;</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Absence of a Duty of Care Analysis</EM>:</TI>
<P><P1>(f) The Divisional Court erred in failing to conduct a full <EM>Anns</EM> / <EM>Cooper</EM> analysis to determine whether the allegation that Crown Attorneys have a duty of care in tort to the police has no reasonable prospect of success.</P1>
<P1>(g) Having failed to conduct a full <EM>Anns/Cooper</EM> analysis, and absent a complete evidentiary record, the court erred in finding that broad policy considerations support the conclusion that Crown Attorneys should be immune from claims for negligent legal advice provided to the police in the course of an investigation of a suspect.</P1></P>
<P>11. The appeal raises issues of general public importance relating to whether a Crown Attorney can be held liable for negligent legal advice provided to the police concerning steps taken in the course of an investigation of an individual suspect.</P>
<P>12. In dismissing the appeal, the Divisional Court did not address the apparent conflict its decision creates with respect to the recently recognized tort of negligent investigation as against police officers as compared to the complete immunity provided to Crown Attorneys for their role in an investigation (not prosecution). There is no principled basis on which Crown Attorneys should be treared any differently than police officers in this regard.</P>
<P>13. The issues involved in this case have not previously been addressed by an appellate court. The issues involved have great importance to the public generally and to the administration of justice.</P>
<P>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</P>
<P>14. Leave to appeal from the Divisional Court was granted on July 5, 2018 pursuant to Section 6(i)(a) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43 and Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
